             the elder.</p>
               <p>ROBERT PICKRELL. I am a bricklayer. The prisoner was employed by me at Mr. Sex's; I sent 60 or 70 lbs. of copper to his hay-loft, and saw it there; I was sent to look for it, and missed it - I believe this to be part of it.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. DOWLING. Q. At the examination you said you could not swear to the copper? A. No; there is no mark on it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290611-359-person2500">
                  CHARLES 
                  JAMES
               <interp inst="t18290611-359-person2500" type="surname" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-359-person2500" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-359-person2500" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             LAWRENCE. I live with Mr. Stanley, a metal dealer. I bought about 11lbs. of this copper of the prisoner, on the 6th of June; he came alone, and said he came from No. 9, Field-lane, and his name was Curton.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Did you not say at Guildhall that Crawley sold all but one piece? A. No; Nowland sold more than he did: I know nothing of the prisoner but by his selling copper at our shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290611-359-verdict1883" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290611-359-verdict1883" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 36.</p>
